 name, perhaps from Brimley in Devon or Brimbley in Stoke Abbott, Dorset, both named with Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","variant of   Bromley  .","English:"]},{"name":"Brumley","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bromley  . This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Bromley was born in 1410, in Kent, England. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with John Middleton. She died in 1446, at the age of 36."},"et":{"1410–1446":"1410–1446","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1430–1509":"1430–1509","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1446":"1446","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1509":"1509","about 1440":"